Step 3: Request SSL Certificate
Go to AWS Certificate Manager  (Must be in us-east-1 for CloudFront)
Click Request a certificate
Choose Request a public certificate
Domain names:
your-domain.com
www.your-domain.com
Validation method: Choose DNS validation (recommended)
Request certificate
Create DNS records in Route 53 (if using Route 53, there's a button to do this automatically)
Step 4: Create CloudFront Distribution
Go to CloudFront Console 
Click Create distribution
Origin Settings:
Origin domain: Use your S3 website endpoint (e.g., your-bucket.s3-website-us-east-1.amazonaws.com)
Protocol: HTTP only (S3 website endpoints don't support HTTPS)
Default Cache Behavior:
Viewer protocol policy: Redirect HTTP to HTTPS
Allowed HTTP methods: GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, PUT, POST, PATCH, DELETE
Cache policy: Managed-CachingOptimized
Settings:
Alternate domain names (CNAMEs): your-domain.com, www.your-domain.com
Custom SSL certificate: Select your ACM certificate
Default root object: index.html
Create distribution (takes 15-20 minutes to deploy)
Step 5: Configure Route 53 DNS
Go to Route 53 Console 
Select your hosted zone
Create A Records:
Create record
Record name: Leave blank (for root domain)
Record type: A
Alias: Yes
Route traffic to: Alias to CloudFront distribution
Choose distribution: Select your CloudFront distribution
Create records
Create WWW Record:
Create record
Record name: www
Record type: A
Alias: Yes
Route traffic to: Alias to CloudFront distribution
Choose distribution: Select your CloudFront distribution
Create records
